\begin_layout Standard
Electroweak baryogenesis (EWBG) is a hypothetical process which may have
 taken place in the very early universe, when the temperature of the universe
 was of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim100\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

.
 EWBG creates an asymmetry in the abundance of baryons (protons, neutrons
 and related particles which also have the quantum numbers of three bound
 quarks) and anti-baryons.
 This asymmetry persists after the universe cools down and is ultimately
 responsible for the abundance of matter in the universe.
 EWBG is considered in this section as a case study of a real physics proposal
 intimately involving both non-perturbative and non-equilibrium aspects.
 As such, it is difficult to compute accurate and reliable EWBG predictions
 from fundamental physics.
 The purpose of the following discussion is to highlight these aspects of
 EWBG, not to give a comprehensive review of the current state of the field.
 For more detailed treatments the reader is encouraged to consult the original
 literature cited below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well known that for every type of matter particle (electron, proton,
 neutron, quarks etc.) there is a corresponding antiparticle with the same
 mass and opposite charge.
 This is now understood to be a consequence of combining the principles
 of special relativity and quantum mechanics, which requires that antiparticles
 exist and have closely related properties to the corresponding particles
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is sometimes said that neutral particles such as the photon and Higgs
 boson have no anti-particles, or that they are their own anti-particles.
 This is a matter of semantics, not physics, and the two descriptions are
 equivalent.
 The convention of this thesis is that 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 particle species have a corresponding anti-particle species (which is sometimes
 identical to the particle species).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This is a very robust result, requiring only basic physical principles,
 and it is satisfied by the SM.
 Further, the standard cosmological model of the universe with a cosmological
 constant and cold dark matter (
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM) predicts that the early universe was in a very hot and dense state,
 where the maximum temperature that the universe reaches could be as high
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{12}\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buchmuller2012a"

\end_inset

.
 At extremely high temperatures the universe contains a plasma where particle
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

)/antiparticle (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\psi}$
\end_inset

) pair creation and annihilation reactions such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\gamma\leftrightarrow\psi\bar{\psi}$
\end_inset

 are in equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the universe expands it cools, and when the temperature drops below 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim m_{\psi}c^{2}/k_{B}$
\end_inset

 the creation reactions 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\gamma\to\psi\bar{\psi}$
\end_inset

 become Boltzmann suppressed.
 However, the annihilation reaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\bar{\psi}\to\gamma\gamma$
\end_inset

 remains efficient as long as the (thermally averaged) reaction rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\sim\left\langle n\sigma v\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number density, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the annihilation cross section and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the relative velocity, is more rapid than the Hubble expansion rate
 of the universe 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\dot{a}/a$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the cosmic scale factor.
 In this regime particle/antiparticle pairs are annihilated, depleting the
 number densities of both and temporarily slowing the cooling of the plasma.
 Once 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\lesssim H$
\end_inset

 the annihilation reactions shut off and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi,\bar{\psi}$
\end_inset

 effectively decouple from the plasma, a phenomenon known as 
\emph on
freeze out
\emph default
.
 After freeze out the 
\emph on
relic densities
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\psi\left(\bar{\psi}\right)}\propto a^{-3}$
\end_inset

 simply track the expansion of the universe.
 (This story assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 particles are stable for simplicity.) Thus one should expect the number
 density of any species to be determined by the mass, reaction rates and
 expansion history in the way described, allowing one to derive from a model
 of particle physics a prediction for the amount of matter and antimatter
 in the universe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relic densities derived this way for the SM lead immediately to two
 puzzles: first, they are too small by about ten orders of magnitude 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cline2006"

\end_inset

, far too small for galaxies to form, and the density of matter and antimatter
 should be comparable.
 Yet astronomical observations have convincingly shown that the universe
 is made of matter.
 The abundance of antimatter is negligible compared to that of matter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Canetti2012"

\end_inset

.
 The baryon asymmetry of the universe (BAU) has been measured at the time
 of 
\emph on
big bang nucleosynthesis
\emph default
 (
\noun on
BBN
\noun default
), about three minutes after the big bang, using the abundances of light
 elements as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Weinberg2008,Steigman2010"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta\equiv\frac{n_{B}-n_{\bar{B}}}{n_{\gamma}}=\begin{cases}
\left(5.9\pm0.5\right)\times10^{-10}, & \text{Kirkman \emph{et al.}, cited in {\citep{Weinberg2008}}},\\
\left(5.8\pm0.27\right)\times10^{-10}, & \text{{\citet{Steigman2010}}},
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B\left(\bar{B}\right)}$
\end_inset

 are the number densities of (anti-)baryons and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is the number density of photons.
 This ratio should be conserved with the expansion of the universe since
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B,\bar{B},\gamma}$
\end_inset

 all scale the same way with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(t\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Up to a threshold correction due to electron/positron freeze out 
\begin_inset Formula $e\bar{e}\to\gamma\gamma$
\end_inset

 at temperatures 
\begin_inset Formula $T\sim m_{e}c^{2}/k_{B}$
\end_inset

, which is straightforward to correct for.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus an independent confirmation can be obtained from the cosmic microwave
 background, and the latest Planck data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ThePlanckCollaboration2013"

\end_inset

 is in agreement
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Planck measured the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}h^{2}=0.02207\pm0.00033$
\end_inset

 which is converted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\Omega_{b}h^{2}/\left(3.65\times10^{7}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Canetti2012,Weinberg2008"

\end_inset

 for further details.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\left(6.05\pm0.09\right)\times10^{-10}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest possible explanation for the observed 
\noun on
BAU
\noun default
 is that it stems from an asymmetry of the initial condition of the universe.
 However a net baryon number 
\begin_inset Formula $B\neq0$
\end_inset

 initial condition for the universe is implausible as a solution to this
 problem for several reasons.
 First, if cosmic inflation is indeed the solution to the horizon, flatness
 and monopole problems in cosmology this requires at least about 60 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folds of expansion which would greatly dilute any initial baryon asymmetry.
 Second, if baryon number conservation is violated by any beyond standard
 model (
\noun on
BSM
\noun default
) physics at high energies then any initial 
\begin_inset Formula $B\neq0$
\end_inset

 would be washed out when the universe comes into chemical equilibrium at
 a temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T\gg T_{EW}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{EW}\sim100\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 is the electroweak scale of the SM.
 Third, the SM itself violates 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 conservation and lepton number 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 conservation through non-perturbative 
\emph on
sphaleron
\emph default
 processes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Arnold1987"

\end_inset

.
 The only exactly conserved flavour quantum number of the SM is the combination
 
\begin_inset Formula $B-L$
\end_inset

.
 Any initial asymmetry in the orthogonal channel 
\begin_inset Formula $B+L$
\end_inset

 will be washed out by sphaleron processes at 
\begin_inset Formula $T>T_{EW}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that at temperatures 
\begin_inset Formula $T<T_{EW}$
\end_inset

 sphalerons are exponentially suppressed and unobservable, hence this scenario
 is compatible with constraints on unobserved processes like proton decay
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\to e^{+}\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the BAU cannot be the result of an asymmetric initial condition it must
 be generated dynamically by some new BSM particle physics.
 This is called 
\emph on
baryogenesis
\emph default
.
 Numerous recent reviews of popular scenarios are available 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cline2006,Dine2003,Morrissey2012,Riotto1999,Shaposhnikov2009,Trodden1998,Trodden2004"

\end_inset

.
 In 1967, Sakharov 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sakharov1991,Dine2003"

\end_inset

 laid out three general conditions which are required to dynamically generate
 
\begin_inset Formula $B\neq0$
\end_inset

 from a symmetrical initial state
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that, although the Sakharov's original paper dealt with a particular
 model of baryogenesis, his three conditions are completely general.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Baryon number violation: Obviously if 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is conserved then 
\begin_inset Formula $B\neq0$
\end_inset

 cannot be generated from a state with 
\begin_inset Formula $B=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Out of equilibrium dynamics: If the universe is in thermal equilibrium then
 every 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-violating reaction is balanced by the reverse reaction and no net asymmetry
 can be generated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 violation: If charge conjugation (
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

) or charge-parity conjugation (
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

) is preserved then for every 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-violating reaction there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 conjugate reaction that has the same rate but opposite 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 asymmetry.
 Hence every 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-violating reaction is balanced by another reaction with the opposite effect
 and no net 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can be created.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SM has all three of the necessary ingredients: 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 violating sphaleron processes come from the non-perturbative electroweak
 sector of the SM, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is maximally violated by the chiral fermion couplings of the weak interactions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 is violated by the complex phase in the Cabibbo-Kobayashi-Maskawa (CKM)
 mixing matrix in the quark sector, and the SM plasma could be driven out
 of equilibrium by the electroweak phase transition (EWPT).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For sufficiently small Higgs mass the EWPT is a first order transition which
 proceeds by bubble formation, analogous to boiling water, a violent process
 that locally departs from thermal equilibrium at the bubble walls.
 It was within the realm of possibility then, before the late 1990s (when
 the LEP2 experiment began placing limits on the Higgs mass), that the SM
 alone could account for baryogenesis.
 However, it is now known that the Higgs mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}=126\ \mathrm{GeV}>72\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $72\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 is the critical point of the EWPT.
 For values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}$
\end_inset

 greater than the critical value the EWPT is a smooth crossover transition
 which does not depart from equilibrium.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}$
\end_inset

 is too large for the EWPT to depart from equilibrium, violating the second
 Sakharov condition.
 Further, detailed computations show that the 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 violating phase of the CKM matrix is many orders of magnitude too small
 to account for the observed BAU 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dine2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the time of Sakharov, numerous models have been proposed that satisfy
 the Sakharov criteria.
 A recent review counted 44 scenarios in the literature for generating the
 BAU 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shaposhnikov2009"

\end_inset

.
 Of those only a handful are well motivated and provide decent prospects
 for experimental confrontation in the foreseeable future.
 These are the models that propose new particles at or below the electroweak
 scale.
 One prominent option is to include additional scalar fields that couple
 to the SM Higgs and strengthen the EWPT, and may also provide new sources
 of CP violation.
 Such scalars can come from supersymmetric (
\noun on
SUSY
\noun default
) extensions of the SM, such as the well studied 
\emph on
minimal SUSY extension of the SM
\emph default
 (MSSM), or from grand unified theories (GUTs).
 These models are classified as 
\emph on
electroweak baryogenesis
\emph default
 (
\noun on
EWBG
\noun default
) scenarios since they all involve the EWPT in an extended electroweak/Higgs
 sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
EWBG was first investigated in the SM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McLerran1989"

\end_inset

, however, with the measured Higgs mass, modern EWBG scenarios are all formulate
d in more or less minimal extensions of the SM such as the 
\noun on
MSSM
\noun default
, the 
\emph on
next to minimal SUSY extension
\emph default
 (
\noun on
NMSSM
\noun default
) with a single extra gauge singlet chiral superfield, and non-SUSY extensions
 such as the 
\emph on
two Higgs doublet models
\emph default
 (
\noun on
2HDM
\noun default
).
 In all of these models the EWBG scenario relies on non-perturbative processes
 very similar to those of the original SM.
 The SM is briefly reviewed here, without going into the formal field theory,
 to recall the physics and discuss EWBG at first in a familiar context.
 This review is by no means comprehensive, nor suitable for a first introduction.
 Up to date topical reviews are available from the Particle Data Group 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Olive2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

