\begin_layout Standard
Due to an ordering interaction of the Higgs field, the electrically neutral
 component of the Higgs doublet develops an expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 When this happens the electroweak symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $SU\left(2\right)_{L}\times U\left(1\right)_{Y}$
\end_inset

 is no longer manifest.
 Instead the weak bosons 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{0}$
\end_inset

 gain mass by the Higgs mechanism, while the remaining electroweak boson
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 becomes the massless photon.
 The masses of the weak gauge bosons are
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{W}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{Z}$
\end_inset

 is modified by radiative corrections.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{W}=gv/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{Z}=m_{W}/\cos\theta_{W}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{W}$
\end_inset

 is the Weinberg angle given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{W}=g/\sqrt{g^{2}+g'^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 The fundamental electric charge is identified as 
\begin_inset Formula $e=g\sin\theta_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 The fermions couple to the Higgs doublet with 
\emph on
Yukawa
\emph default
 couplings 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 which, after symmetry breaking, result in fermion masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}=y_{i}v$
\end_inset

.
 All of the SM fermions gain their mass in this way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally notice that the 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 field equations of the SM conserve baryon number 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and lepton number 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 as defined by Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:standard-model-fermions"

\end_inset

.
 These generate a 
\emph on
global 
\emph default
(not gauged) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{U}\left(1\right)_{B}\times\mathrm{U}\left(1\right)_{L}$
\end_inset

 symmetry of the theory.
 This is an accidental symmetry in that it was not put in by design, but
 is rather a result of the fact that the only terms possible to write down
 with the given fields 
\emph on
happen
\emph default
 to obey it.
 However, symmetries of theories with chiral fermions coupled to gauge bosons
 are spoiled 
\emph on
chiral anomalies
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Peskin1995,Shaposhnikov1991"

\end_inset

 and indeed quantum effects reduce the global symmetry group to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{U}\left(1\right)_{B-L}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $B+L$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 a conserved quantum number of the SM at a quantum level, but 
\begin_inset Formula $B-L$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
is
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mechanism of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 violation is topological in nature and as such is invisible to perturbation
 theory.
 At zero temperature it proceeds by quantum tunnelling between gauge vacua
 with different topologies.
 A potential barrier separates these field configurations and the leading
 contribution to the transition rate at zero temperature comes from the
 semi-classical tunnelling trajectory called an 
\emph on
instanton
\emph default
 (see, e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hooft1976,Coleman1985"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kuzmin1985"

\end_inset

 argued that at finite temperature the transition proceeds by classical
 fluctuations 
\emph on
over the barrier
\emph default
 at a rate increasing exponentially with temperature, finally becoming unsuppres
sed entirely at sufficiently high temperature.
 The height of the barrier can be computed by finding the (unstable) configurati
on of the gauge and Higgs fields that maximises the energy atop the barrier.
 These configurations are called 
\emph on
sphalerons
\emph default
 and were discovered by Klinkhamer and Manton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Klinkhamer1984"

\end_inset

.
 Further early analysis of these configurations in the SM were carried out
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Arnold1987"

\end_inset

.
 Pedagogical discussions can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shaposhnikov1991,Shifman2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weak gauge fields possess a topological invariant called the 
\emph on
Chern-Simons
\emph default
 number 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 which, effectively, measures how many times the gauge field configuration
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

winds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 around the sphere at infinity.
 In vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 is an integer.
 Transitions from one gauge vacuum to another are possible and when this
 happens the chiral anomaly is responsible for changing 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B=\Delta L=3\Delta\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

.
 More generally 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B=\Delta L=n_{g}\Delta\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{g}$
\end_inset

 is the number of fermion generations.
 One can sketch the potential energy along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in field space as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chern-simons-potential-su2-theory"

\end_inset

.
 The sphaleron is the minimal energy configuration interpolating between
 two adjacent vacua (i.e., the smallest barrier).
 Note that this figure is only illustrative.
 To find an honest expression for the potential energy one needs to develop
 a one parameter ansatz for the gauge and Higgs fields which passes through
 the vacuum and sphaleron field configurations at appropriate parameter
 values and compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and the energy of the field configuration as a function of the parameter.
 The resulting figure is somewhat arbitrary, depending on the choice of
 ansatz.
 Physically, there are many paths over the ridge in field space represented
 by the sphaleron.
