\begin_layout Standard
The height of the barrier and the sphaleron solution are found from a static
 configuration of the gauge and Higgs fields that extremises the energy
 subject to the boundary conditions imposed by the required Chern-Simons
 number.
 The resulting field profiles must be found numerically 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Klinkhamer1984"

\end_inset

, but in the 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\to0$
\end_inset

 limit they depend only on the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{2}/g^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Higgs self-coupling.
 The energy can then be written
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=\frac{4\pi v}{g}C\left(\frac{\lambda^{2}}{g^{2}}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the numerical factor 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\lambda^{2}/g^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 has been estimated in the original literature.
 Its precise value is not important here, but 
\begin_inset Formula $C\sim\mathcal{O}\left(1-3\right)$
\end_inset

 for the whole range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{2}/g^{2}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $+\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the height of the barrier at zero temperature is of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10\ \mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

.
 One can thus think of the sphaleron, very roughly, as an unstable bound
 configuration with of the order of 30 each of 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{+},W^{-},Z$
\end_inset

 and 10 Higgs particles in a region 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{-17}\ \mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

 across.
 In reality the sphaleron is a coherent state, not a particle number eigenstate,
 so this picture is at best qualitative.
 However, this illustrates that, while 
\begin_inset Formula $10\ \mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

 might not sound like a terribly high energy for modern colliders, sphalerons
 are difficult if not impossible to produce at present day collider experiments
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Shifman2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second Sakharov criterion requires that the early universe depart from
 thermal equilibrium at some point.
 This is achieved in EWBG by a first order phase transition associated with
 electroweak symmetry breaking.
 Recall that if the Higgs field(s) has a non-vanishing expectation value
 the electroweak symmetry is said to be broken, while if the expectation
 value is zero the symmetry is manifest or unbroken.
 The behaviour of the Higgs field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in equilibrium can be determined by minimising the effective potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 is determined from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\phi\right]$
\end_inset

, which is the (Euclidean) 
\emph on
one particle irreducible
\emph default
 
\emph on
effective action
\emph default
 of the Higgs field.
 This formalism will be discussed in detail in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap2"

\end_inset

.
 The effective potential can be computed in a semi-classical expansion in
 powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

.
 The lowest order term is just the classical Higgs potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\left(0\right)}\left(\phi\right)=\mu^{2}\phi^{2}+\frac{\lambda^{2}}{2}\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 The first correction is due to Feynman diagrams with one loop, which can
 be summed up to 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\left(1\right)}\left(\phi\right)=V_{\mathrm{vac}}^{\left(1\right)}\left(\phi\right)+V^{\left(1\right)}\left(\phi,T\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{vac}}^{\left(1\right)}\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 is the contribution present at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

 which serves to renormalise
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This ignores the logarithmic Coleman-Weinberg terms, which can be justified
 by choosing an appropriate renormalisation scale.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the parameters in 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\left(0\right)}\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\left(1\right)}\left(\phi,T\right)$
\end_inset

 is the temperature dependent correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Konstandin2013,Dine1992,Kapusta2006"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V^{\left(1\right)}\left(\phi,T\right)=\sum_{i}\Delta V_{i}^{\left(1\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum runs over all species.
 One can assume that the universe as a whole is neutral and that 
\begin_inset Formula $B-L=0$
\end_inset

 because the baryon asymmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\sim6\times10^{-10}$
\end_inset

 is small and is expected to have only a small impact on the thermal properties
 of the early plasma.
 For illustrative purposes it is good enough to perform a high temperature
 expansion of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V_{i}^{\left(1\right)}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ll T$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kapusta2006"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta V_{\text{fermions}}^{\left(1\right)} & =-\frac{7\pi^{2}}{720}T^{4}+\frac{1}{48}m^{2}T^{2}+\mathcal{O}\left(m^{4}\right),\\
\Delta V_{\text{bosons}}^{\left(1\right)} & =-\frac{\pi^{2}}{90}T^{4}+\frac{1}{24}m^{2}T^{2}-\frac{1}{12\pi}m^{3}T+\mathcal{O}\left(m^{4}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

For a species obtaining mass from the Higgs, 
\begin_inset Formula $m\sim g\phi$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m\sim y\phi$
\end_inset

 for gauge bosons and fermions respectively.
 Thus the terms independent of the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 give a 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 independent contribution to the potential, thus having no impact on the
 derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}V/\mathrm{d}\phi$
\end_inset

 or the location of the extrema, hence these can be ignored for present
 purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate a first order phase transition assume (incorrectly) that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}<m_{W},m_{Z},m_{t}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 that the Higgs boson is lighter than the 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and top quarks, and ignore the contributions of all particles lighter than
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 bosons since the heavy particles have a correspondingly greater coupling
 to the Higgs field.
 The assumption that the Higgs is light allows the use of perturbation theory.
 Higher order loop corrections involving 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 bosons come in with an expansion parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim m_{H}^{2}/m_{W}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and perturbation theory breaks down for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}\gtrsim m_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 Lattice computations have shown that the line of first order phase transitions
 terminates in a second order critical point at 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}\sim70\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 and for the physical Higgs mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}\sim125\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 there is no phase transition between the broken and symmetric phases, only
 a smooth crossover 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kapusta2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effective potential in this case is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:first-order-transition-free-energy"

\end_inset

.
 To leading order in the loop and high 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 expansions 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{eff}}\left(\phi,T\right)=\left(-\frac{m_{H}^{2}}{2v^{2}}+a\frac{T^{2}}{v^{2}}\right)\frac{\phi^{2}}{v^{2}}-b\frac{T}{v}\frac{\phi^{3}}{v^{3}}+\frac{m_{H}^{2}}{4v^{2}}\frac{\phi^{4}}{v^{4}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{1}{8}y_{t}^{2}+\frac{1+2\cos^{2}\theta_{W}}{16\cos^{2}\theta_{W}}g^{2}\approx0.2$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the top quark Yukawa coupling) is not to be confused with the cosmological
 scale factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\frac{1+2\cos^{3}\theta_{W}}{8\pi\sqrt{2}\cos^{3}\theta_{W}}g^{3}\approx0.03$
\end_inset

.
 In the plots 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}=0.1v\sim18\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 for illustrative purposes.
 At temperatures above the upper spinodal temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{+}=\frac{2m_{H}^{2}}{\sqrt{8am_{H}^{2}-9b^{2}v^{2}}}\approx0.225v$
\end_inset

 the minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 is the only critical point of the effective potential and the electroweak
 symmetry is manifest.
 Between the upper and lower spinodal temperatures, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{+}>T>T_{-}=\frac{m_{H}}{\sqrt{2a}}\approx0.158v$
\end_inset

, a second minimum develops at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\neq0$
\end_inset

 which is separated by a barrier from the minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 At the critical temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\star}\approx0.213v$
\end_inset

 the new minimum is degenerate with the minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 At temperatures 
\begin_inset Formula $T<T_{\star}$
\end_inset

 the broken phase is preferred and for 
\begin_inset Formula $T<T_{-}$
\end_inset

 the coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{eff}}$
\end_inset

 vanishes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 ceases to be a minimum of the effective potential altogether.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The history of the universe in this scenario is as follows.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $T>T_{+}$
\end_inset

 the electroweak symmetry is unbroken.
 As the universe expands the temperature drops to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\star}<T<T_{+}$
\end_inset

.
 In this regime bubbles of broken phase can form by thermal fluctuations
 but these are unstable and rapidly disappear.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{\star}$
\end_inset

 the interior of the bubbles of broken phase are degenerate with the unbroken
 phase, but there is an energy cost associated with the bubble walls that
 still renders them unstable.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{-}<T<T_{\star}$
\end_inset

 the broken phase has an energy advantage 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V=-V_{\mathrm{eff}}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{min}},T\right)$
\end_inset

 and a spherical bubble of broken phase has an energy
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=4\pi R^{2}\sigma-\frac{4\pi}{3}R^{3}\Delta V,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the surface tension of the bubble wall.
 The bubble will expand if it is larger than the critical size 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\star}=2\sigma/\Delta V$
\end_inset

.
 The rate of bubble formation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\sim\exp\left(-E_{\star}/T\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\star}=\frac{16\pi}{3}\frac{\sigma^{3}}{\Delta V^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the energy of the critical bubble.
 Bubble nucleation becomes cosmologically significant when this rate exceeds
 the Hubble rate, which requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 drop sufficiently below 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 At this time bubbles begin to form and expand, eventually filling the universe.
 The volume fraction of broken phase as a function of time and the completion
 time of the phase transition can be computed from a simple macroscopic
 model once a few plasma parameters are known, namely the latent heat, surface
 tension and wall velocity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rubakov1996,Huber2013"

\end_inset

.
 The wall velocity in turn can be calculated using a hydrodynamic theory
 given the friction on the bubble wall, at least for sufficiently large
 bubbles in the thin wall limit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Huber2013"

\end_inset

.
 It is the job of a micro-physical model to calculate the wall friction,
 latent heat and surface tension of a phase transition bubble.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The friction on bubble walls is the result of particles in the unbroken
 phase scattering on the bubble wall and being driven out of local thermal
 equilibrium.
 It is this breaking of local thermal equilibrium which satisfies the Sakharov
 criterion for baryogenesis in EWBG models.
 If the scatterings also violate 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 by preferentially scattering left handed particles, then a net asymmetry
 of left handed particles builds up in the unbroken phase in front of the
 wall (balanced by an opposite right handed asymmetry which passes through
 the wall).
 The left handed particles outside the wall bias sphaleron transitions to
 produce a net baryon number.
 It is important that in the broken phase the sphaleron transitions are
 turned off, otherwise they will wash out the net asymmetry.
 This requires that the phase transition be sufficiently strong, typically
 taken to mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi/T_{\star}\gtrsim1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 is the difference in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 between the phases at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\star}$
\end_inset

, but it is not trivial to determine how strong is really strong enough.
 Indeed, a proper determination of the washout factor, beyond a few conservative
 estimates, is one of the main outstanding problems in EWBG 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morrissey2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The qualitative reason 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 violation leads to baryogenesis is as follows.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 is violated in quark-wall scattering such that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{L}+\bar{q}_{R}$
\end_inset

 reflect more readily than 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{R}+\bar{q}_{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, temporarily 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

turn off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sphalerons for illustrative purposes.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{R}+\bar{q}_{L}$
\end_inset

 build up in front of the bubble wall (recall that Higgs-Yukawa interactions
 change fermion chirality) while a compensating 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 asymmetry passes through into the broken phase.
 There is no baryon asymmetry at this stage, and if it were not for sphaleron
 transitions no asymmetry would be generated: though the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{R}+\bar{q}_{L}$
\end_inset

 tend to reflect from the bubble wall they will all eventually pass through,
 certainly by the time the broken phase fills all of space.
 Now turn sphalerons back on.
 Sphalerons only act on the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 particles, converting 
\begin_inset Formula $3n_{f}\bar{q}_{L}\to n_{f}l_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3n_{f}q_{L}\to n_{f}\bar{l}_{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The rate of the former process, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B=+1$
\end_inset

, exceeds the rate of the latter, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B=-1$
\end_inset

, since there are more 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{L}$
\end_inset

 than 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{L}$
\end_inset

 in front of the wall.
 Hence a net baryon number is generated in front of the bubble wall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly the net baryon asymmetry produced by this mechanism depends on a
 number of factors: how strong is the 
\begin_inset Formula $CP$
\end_inset

 violation in the reflection/transmission coefficients; how far do reflected
 particles diffuse into the plasma ahead of the bubble wall and for how
 long; what is the rate of sphaleron transitions in the plasma ahead of
 and behind the bubble wall; and how fast are other processes besides sphalerons
 which tend to wash out CP asymmetries (without producing B or L asymmetries)?
 The current practice for quantitative calculations is to: (1) calculate
 bubble wall reflection/transmission coefficients using a non-equilibrium
 quantum transport theory or semi-classical Boltzmann equation, using bubble
 wall velocities obtained from a hydrodynamic treatment and ignoring the
 back-reaction of the generated asymmetries on the bubble wall; (2) perform
 lattice Monte Carlo calculations of the sphaleron rate, in one of a few
 simplified models, in equilibrium at various temperatures to calibrate
 a semi-empirical formula which hopefully applies out of equilibrium to
 the required accuracy; and (3) combine these elements in a network of continuit
y equations which are integrated numerically to find the final baryon (and
 lepton) asymmetry 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morrissey2012,Konstandin2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By way of contrast, a second order phase transition is illustrated in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
