\begin_layout Standard
The obvious major problem facing EWBG scenarios is the order of the electroweak
 phase transition.
 It is necessary for the transition to proceed through bubble formation
 as in a first order transition, and also that the scalar field behind the
 bubble wall be sufficiently large (a measure of the strength of the phase
 transition) that sphaleron processes are effectively shut off, lest they
 erase the baryon asymmetry that was so painstakingly created.
 The most straightforward approach to strengthening the EWPT is adding new
 scalar fields which are strongly coupled to the Higgs.
 However, any models with new particles necessarily have undetermined parameters
 which must be scanned to assess the range of EWBG predictions possible.
 Typically perturbation theory is used since it is relatively easy to scan
 parameters, however perturbative results do not necessarily agree with
 more accurate (but harder to scan) lattice methods.
 See e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chung2013"

\end_inset

 for a perturbative discussion of EWBG in the MSSM and contrast this with
 the lattice Monte Carlo studies using dimensional reduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kajantie1996,Laine2012,Laine2013"

\end_inset

 which suggest that the EWPT can be much stronger than the perturbative
 estimates.
 Unfortunately these lattice methods have been applied only to a few well
 studied models such as the MSSM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to investigate new physics in a fairly model independent
 way if a few simplifying assumptions are satisfied.
 If the new physics, however complicated, exists at a scale 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 which is heaver than the weak scale 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, and there exists a separation scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v\ll\Lambda\lesssim M$
\end_inset

 then it is possible to use an effective field theory below the scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 with only the SM degrees of freedom.
 The new physics manifests as additional operators in the Lagrangian:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{SM}}+\sum_{i}\frac{1}{\Lambda}c_{i}^{\left(5\right)}\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5\right)}+\sum_{i}\frac{1}{\Lambda^{2}}c_{i}^{\left(6\right)}\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(6\right)}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\Lambda^{3}}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 are the set of all gauge invariant operators of mass dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 respectively built only out of SM fields
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Do not confuse the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 with the mathematical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

big-oh
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 are dimensionless (
\emph on
Wilson
\emph default
) coefficients which are expected to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 if they come from a generic model of new physics (if the new physics has
 a symmetry some of the coefficients can vanish, or be loop suppressed).
 Amplitudes calculated in the effective theory are expected to be accurate
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(E/\Lambda\right)^{3}$
\end_inset

 corrections, where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is energy scale for the process at hand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A complete basis of linearly independent operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}^{\left(5,6\right)}$
\end_inset

 has been found for the SM degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grzadkowski2010"

\end_inset

.
 Altogether there are 65 of them: one dimension 5 term that generates Majorana
 neutrino masses after electroweak symmetry breaking, and 64 dimension 6
 operators: 59 of which conserve 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, and 5 four-fermion contact interactions which violate
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that such operators are typically constrained to a very high scale
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\gtrsim10^{12}\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 as they generate tree-level proton decay, unlike the non-perturbative sphaleron
/instanton processes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (but conserve 
\begin_inset Formula $B-L$
\end_inset

).
 Of all of these operators, only one affects the Higgs potential: the dimension
 six term 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus a conservative, and largely model independent, exploration of BSM
 modifications to the Higgs potential can be achieved by taking as the Higgs
 potential
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(\phi\right)=\mu^{2}\phi^{2}+\frac{\lambda}{2}\phi^{4}+\frac{1}{\Lambda^{2}}\phi^{6}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

EWBG with this potential has been investigated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grojean2005"

\end_inset

 which finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\sim500-800\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

 gives a strong first order phase transition for the physical Higgs mass
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}=125\ \mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{6}$
\end_inset

 term is very difficult to probe at the LHC, thus the constraints are weak
 unless the new physics generates other dimension 6 operators at the same
 scale.
 As a result, LHC constraints do not yet significantly touch this range
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, though with enough luminosity at 
\begin_inset Formula $14\ \mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

 the LHC could begin to constrain this scenario through measurements of
 the Higgs cubic self-coupling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grojean2005,Chung2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus it is easy to strengthen the EWPT in BSM models of current phenomenological
 interest.
 However, questions can be raised about the computation of the phase transition
 thermodynamics.
 A conceptual question of great practical import is the gauge dependence
 of this theory, which is relevant in the Higgs theory because an expectation
 value of a gauge-variant quantity like 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is physically meaningless.
 Two methods are available to check the gauge dependence of the result:
 redo the computation in a general class of gauges such as the 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\xi}$
\end_inset

 gauge and check the dependence on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 parameter, or develop a formulation using only manifestly gauge invariant
 quantities.
 An example of the first method is the jump of the order parameter at the
 critical temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}/T_{c}$
\end_inset

, calculated by standard techniques in the SM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Patel2011"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\phi_{c}}{T_{c}}=\frac{3-\xi^{3/2}}{48\pi\lambda}\left(2g_{2}^{3}+\left(g_{1}^{2}+g_{2}^{2}\right)^{3/2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the Higgs quartic coupling and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{U}\left(1\right),\ \mathrm{SU}\left(2\right)_{L}$
\end_inset

 gauge couplings respectively (note the normalisation convention for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is different from the one used here!).
 Note the spurious gauge dependence of this quantity.
 Indeed by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=3^{2/3}$
\end_inset

 the order parameter can be made to vanish! Similarly, calculations of the
 sphaleron rate and washout factors are gauge dependent and so far only
 lattice results are theoretically solid, but these have only been done
 in a small number of cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morrissey2012"

\end_inset

.
 As a result it is difficult to say whether a given phase transition is
 indeed strong enough to avoid washing out a baryon asymmetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of the second method is the lattice Monte Carlo method, where
 it is necessary to use gauge invariant order parameters from the outset
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Moore1997,Boedeker2000"

\end_inset

 for examples showing how gauge invariant observables can be judiciously
 chosen to extract the desired physics).
 Unfortunately it is infeasible to implement and interpret lattice computations
 for every scenario in every model of interest, so it remains valuable to
 develop appropriately gauge invariant perturbative methods.
 Also, lattice methods can only be straightforwardly applied to equilibrium
 problems.
 Thus real time methods which allow an extension to non-equilibrium situations
 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 have manifestly good gauge invariance properties are particularly valuable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once a first order phase transition is in hand, the probability of bubble
 formation can be found in equilibrium by saddle-point evaluation of the
 Euclidean functional integral.
 At zero temperature the pioneering theory of Coleman and Callan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Coleman1977,Callan1977"

\end_inset

 remains essentially unmodified (c.f.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dine1992,Linde2005,Shifman2012"

\end_inset

 for more recent discussions).
 They find that the bubble formation probability per unit volume per unit
 time for a single scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and false vacuum solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{+}$
\end_inset

 (with the convention 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(\phi_{+}\right)=0$
\end_inset

) is, to leading semi-classical order,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Gamma}{V}=\mathrm{e}^{-B/\hbar}\frac{B^{2}}{4\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}}\left|\frac{\det'\left[-\partial^{2}+U''\left(\bar{\phi}\right)\right]}{\det\left[-\partial^{2}+U''\left(\phi_{+}\right)\right]}\right|^{-\frac{1}{2}}\left[1+\mathcal{O}\left(\hbar\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
bounce action
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B=\int\mathrm{d}^{4}x_{E}\ \left[\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial\bar{\phi}\right)^{2}+U\left(\bar{\phi}\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\emph default
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\phi}$
\end_inset

 is the solution of the Euclidean (imaginary time) equations of motion with
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mbox{\phi\left(x\to\infty\right)=\phi_{+}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The prime on 
\begin_inset Formula $\det'$
\end_inset

 indicates that the zero modes of the differential operator are excluded
 from the functional determinant.
 The functional integrals over the zero modes correspond to integrating
 over all possible bubble centres and nucleation times, which is accounted
 for by the 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{2}/4\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}$
\end_inset

 pre-factor.
 Extension of the theory to finite temperatures is in principle straightforward:
 one looks for solutions which are periodic in imaginary time with period
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar/k_{B}T$
\end_inset

.
 At high temperatures the problem is effectively reduced to a three dimensional
 one and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\to\frac{\hbar}{k_{B}T}S_{3}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

 is the three dimensional action 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dine1992,Linde2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally the evaluation of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a tractable numerical problem, though analytical results are available
 for the very widely used 
\emph on
thin wall approximation
\emph default
, but the evaluation of the functional determinants ranges from very difficult
 to hopeless.
 Thus one typically 
\emph on
guesses
\emph default
 the pre-factor based on scaling and dimensional analysis and attempts to
 validate this guess by comparison to lattice Monte Carlo simulations.
 So far this program has only been carried out for a small number of benchmark
 models.
 In cases of phenomenological interest for EWBG where multiple scalar fields
 are participating in the phase transition the nucleation rate is in principle
 a straightforward extension of these standard results, but the computational
 difficulty increases with the complexity of the scalar sector.
 Often one finds thin wall results applied without the validity of the approxima
tion being checked.
 Another important question concerns the gauge dependence of the formalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Baryon production is largely dependent on the production of CP violation
 in fermion scattering off bubble walls and the diffusion of the asymmetric
 species into the plasma ahead of the bubble wall, which must be subsonic
 for such diffusion to happen
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Though see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Caprini2011"

\end_inset

 for an alternate EWBG mechanism involving supersonic bubble walls.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The faster an asymmetric species diffuses, the longer it remains ahead
 of the bubble wall, and the longer sphalerons have to convert it into a
 net baryon asymmetry.
 Thus a solid understanding of the scattering and transport of plasma particles
 in the bubble region is essential to a reliable EWBG calculation.
 Recent progress has achieved this, up to some small open questions, in
 the context of the MSSM (for a review see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Konstandin2013"

\end_inset

).
 These techniques have not yet seen wide application to BSM models other
 than the MSSM, although the SM with the dimension six term 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{6}$
\end_inset

, a scalar singlet SM extension, 2HDM (Types I and II), MSSM, and NMSSM
 are each briefly discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Konstandin2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, electroweak baryogenesis is a plausible mechanism for explaining
 one of the greatest mysteries: the matter-antimatter asymmetry of the universe.
 The size of the asymmetry is well established within seconds of the big
 bang, and is crucial for the production of light elements in the early
 universe.
 If it were not for some mechanism of baryogenesis there would be very little
 matter in the universe, and essentially no galaxies, stars, heavy elements
 or life.
 Yet, remarkably, EWBG provides a testable mechanism for controlling the
 late time abundance of matter in the universe and is already being constrained
 by the LHC.
 EWBG in specific models such as the MSSM is already under a great deal
 of strain, although ruling it out in a completely model independent test
 may have to wait for the next collider.
 At the present time experiments are catching up to theoretical speculations
 at the electroweak scale, and formulating solid theoretical predictions
 should be a top priority.
 In particular, it should be possible to say with confidence whether a first
 order phase transition exists in any particular extended Higgs sector,
 and what the critical temperature, nucleation rate, strength of the phase
 transition, CP violation generation rate and sphaleron rates are in all
 relevant regimes.
 These quantities have been well established in a handful of benchmark models
 but for the most part questionable estimates and conservative rules of
 thumb are used to establish the viability of EWBG within a particular model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of this motivates the investigation of a new approach to non-equilibrium
 non-abelian gauge theories, incorporating and extending the new insights
 from recent years to theories of phenomenological interest.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holy grail
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of this investigation would be an approach to Yang-Mills-Higgs-Dirac type
 theories with chiral fermions which is manifestly gauge invariant, can
 solve the initial value problem far from equilibrium, with realistic (i.e.
 non-Gaussian) initial conditions, with a well established and tractable
 renormalisation procedure, while avoiding infrared singularities, unphysical
 transients and secularities though consistent and systematically improvable
 re-summations.
 It would be desirable to see the spontaneous symmetry breaking of a non-abelian
 gauge theory or biased sphaleron transitions in real time, and a controlled
 analytical framework capable of this would provide a valuable check of
 lattice calculations and perhaps provide useful 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

boundary markers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the quest to map out possibilities for beyond standard model physics.
 It is incredible â€“ maybe wildly optimistic â€“ that such a formulation might
 be possible.
 In the meantime one may take some small steps towards this dream by attempting
 to extend the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-particle irreducible effective action formalism, which has already been
 demonstrated to be useful in non-perturbative and non-equilibrium quantum
 field theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Berges2015"

\end_inset

, to better handle theories with a high degree of symmetry and symmetry
 changing phase transitions.
 This hypothesis provides the launching point for this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quantum field theory and functional integrals
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Quantum-field-theory"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The review of electroweak baryogenesis in the preceding section motivates
 the development of new techniques for non-perturbative quantum field theory
 based on the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-particle irreducible effective action formalism.
 However, before diving into that work a brief review of basic quantum field
 theory is worthwhile.
 This is provided here.
 The following review is not comprehensive and cannot replace an actual
 course in quantum field theory, but it does suffice to establish the notation
 and basic framework which forms the basis of the rest of this thesis.
 Further, the original references cited below can provide a jumping off
 point for further investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
field
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 is simply a mapping from a spacetime manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 to a field or 
\emph on
target
\emph default
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 assigning to each event in spacetime the value that the field takes at
 that event.
 This thesis focuses on the special case of scalar fields, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (later on, when discussing symmetries, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\mathbb{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

 for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

).
 This thesis also restricts discussion to flat spacetimes
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The generalisation to curved spacetimes is in some respects straightforward
 and in other respects quite subtle and interesting, though beyond the scope
 of this thesis.
 In any event, quantum field theory in curved spacetime is standard lore
 (see, e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Birrell1984"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\emph on
quantum field
\emph default
 is simply a field which can exist in a quantum superposition of several
 classical states.
 Thus quantum field theory (QFT) is often considered a special case of quantum
 mechanics (QM), taking the limit that the number of degrees of freedom
 goes to infinity.
 However, the limit usually cannot be taken in a rigorous way and in fact
 one proceeds the other way, deriving QM as a special case of QFT in zero
 spatial dimensions (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is just the time-line and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 is a copy of ordinary space for each particle).
 Furthermore, there are non-trivial QFTs with no particle content whatsoever
 (so called 
\emph on
conformal field theories
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
topological field theories
\emph default
).
 Still, there is a close relation between QM and QFT: for each formalism
 available for QM there is a corresponding QFT formalism.
 Thus, for example, one could study quantum fields in the Schr
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
"
\end_layout

\end_inset

odinger picture via the 
\emph on
wavefunctional
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\left[\phi\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 and its evolution equation 
\begin_inset Formula $i\hbar\partial_{t}\Psi=\hat{\mathrm{H}}\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 However, in QFT it is often far more convenient to use the functional integral
 formalism, originally due to Feynman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Feynman2010"

\end_inset

, so this section reviews QFT in the functional formalism and some of the
 connections to the more familiar canonical formalism which will be useful
 later on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start in the canonical formalism.
 Here, fields are Heisenberg picture operators (actually operator valued
 distributions) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 with accompanying canonical momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 which obey canonical 
\emph on
equal time
\emph default
 commutation relationships
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{y},t\right)\right]=\left[\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{y},t\right)\right]=0,\\
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{y},t\right)\right]=i\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{x}-\boldsymbol{y}\right).
\end{gather}

\end_inset

Commutators at unequal times must be found by evolving the field with its
 equations of motion.
 For a free field this can be done exactly.
 The free field Hamiltonian is quadratic in fields and momenta, exactly
 analogous to the QM harmonic oscillator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{0}=\int_{\boldsymbol{x}}\frac{1}{2}\hat{\pi}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\nabla\hat{\phi}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\hat{\phi}^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a parameter with dimensions of inverse length (the name is due to a
 quantity with dimensions of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m\hbar/c$
\end_inset

, which is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in natural units because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=c=1$
\end_inset

).
 The Hamiltonian equations of motion are then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\partial_{t}\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right) & =-i\left[\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{H}_{0}\left(t\right)\right]=\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\\
\partial_{t}\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right) & =-i\left[\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{H}_{0}\left(t\right)\right]=\nabla^{2}\hat{\phi}-m^{2}\hat{\phi},
\end{align}

\end_inset

which can be rearranged to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\partial_{t}^{2}-\nabla^{2}+m^{2}\right)\hat{\phi}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the 
\emph on
Klein-Gordon
\emph default
 equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset

, and an analogous equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}$
\end_inset

.
 As a linear equation, this can be solved by Fourier decomposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right)=\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}N_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}\mathrm{e}^{i\left(\boldsymbol{k}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}t\right)}+\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\mathrm{e}^{-i\left(\boldsymbol{k}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}t\right)}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}=\sqrt{\boldsymbol{k}^{2}+m^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and taking into account that, as a real scalar field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}^{\dagger}=\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the normalisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{\boldsymbol{k}}=\sqrt{\frac{\left(2\pi\right)^{3}}{2\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}f_{\boldsymbol{k}}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and applying the equal time commutation relations leads then to the commutation
 relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}\right]=\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}^{\dagger}\right]=0,\\
\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}^{\dagger}\right]=f_{\boldsymbol{k}}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{q}\right),
\end{gather}

\end_inset

for the mode operators.
 It is conventional to take 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\boldsymbol{k}}=1$
\end_inset

, which is used in all the following.
 With this choice 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\right)$
\end_inset

 are annihilation(creation) operators for particles with bosonic statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the mode expansion the free Hamiltonian becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{0}=\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(2\pi\right)^{3}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}+\frac{1}{2}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the formal commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\right]=\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 was used.
 Using the Fourier representation of the delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)=\left(2\pi\right)^{-3}\int_{\boldsymbol{x}}\mathrm{e}^{i\boldsymbol{x}\cdot\boldsymbol{0}}=\left(2\pi\right)^{-3}\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of space, the second term can be written
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(2\pi\right)^{3}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\frac{1}{2}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)=\left(\frac{1}{2}\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\right)\mathrm{V},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which assigns an energy density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 to the vacuum.
 Subtracting this (divergent) vacuum energy density gives the normal ordered
 Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
:\hat{H}_{0}:=\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{k}\ \omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}a_{\boldsymbol{k}}=\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{k}\ \omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\hat{N}_{\boldsymbol{k}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 is the number operator for the mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $:\hat{H}_{0}:$
\end_inset

 describes non-interacting (because the energy is additive) particle-like
 bosonic excitations of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the unequal time commutator can be found:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(x\right),\hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\right] & =\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}N_{\boldsymbol{k}}\int_{\boldsymbol{q}}N_{\boldsymbol{q}}\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}\mathrm{e}^{ikx}+\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\mathrm{e}^{-ikx},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}\mathrm{e}^{iqy}+\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}^{\dagger}\mathrm{e}^{-iqy}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}N_{\boldsymbol{k}}\int_{\boldsymbol{q}}N_{\boldsymbol{q}}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{q}\right)\left(\mathrm{e}^{i\left(kx-qy\right)}-\mathrm{e}^{-i\left(kx-qy\right)}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\int\frac{\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{k}}{2\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}}\left(\mathrm{e}^{ik\left(x-y\right)}-\mathrm{e}^{-ik\left(x-y\right)}\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the time component of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 in the exponentials.
 Note that when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are spacelike separated, there is a frame in which the time component of
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}-y^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 vanishes.
 In this case one can see that the commutator vanishes by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}\to-\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

 in the second term.
 To show that this holds in all frames one needs to show that the integration
 measure is in fact Lorentz invariant, as the exponentials are manifestly
 invariant.
 Consider the identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}}=\int\mathrm{d}k_{0}\delta\left(k_{0}^{2}-\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{2}\right)\Theta\left(k_{0}\right)=\int\mathrm{d}k_{0}\delta\left(k^{2}-m^{2}\right)\Theta\left(k_{0}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(x\right),\hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\right] & =\int_{k}\left(2\pi\right)^{4}\delta\left(k^{2}-m^{2}\right)\Theta\left(k_{0}\right)\left(\mathrm{e}^{ik\left(x-y\right)}-\mathrm{e}^{-ik\left(x-y\right)}\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is manifestly invariant under the isochronous (i.e.
 not reversing time) Lorentz transformations.
 Thus fields commute at spacelike separation.
 This is the 
\emph on
microcausality
\emph default
 condition and effectively implements the speed of light limit for information
 transmission.
 Microcausality holds for the free field theory, but also for the interacting
 theories of physical interest
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The main exception being electromagnetism in the Coulomb gauge, which explicitly
 breaks Lorentz invariance.
 In this case the (gauge variant) commutators do not vanish at spacelike
 separations but causality problems are avoided because only gauge invariant
 quantities are physically observable.
 All gauge invariant quantities can be equally well computed in a Lorentz
 covariant gauge in which microcausality is manifest at every step.
 For further details, consult e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Weinberg2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and is automatic if the theory is constructed from a Lorentz invariant
 action which is the integral of a local density which is a finite order
 polynomial of fields and their derivatives 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Weinberg2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since spacelike separated fields commute, the set of fields on a spacelike
 hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 forms a complete commuting set of operators and a complete set of eigenvectors
 can be found.
 Arbitrary states can be expanded in this basis as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Ket{\Psi}=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\left(x\in\Sigma\right)\right]\Psi\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]\Ket{\phi\left(x\right);\Sigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 is the wavefunctional and the Heisenberg states 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{\phi\left(x\right);\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 are eigenvectors of the field operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{\phi\left(x\right);\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 is generally 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 an eigenvector of a field operator 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 on the hypersurface.
 The time variable hidden in the notation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is merely part of the label for the state and implies nothing about its
 time evolution (indeed Heisenberg states do not evolve).
 The notation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $;\Sigma$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used to remind us of this fact.
 Now consider a transition amplitude between an initial and final state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{i}\to\Psi_{f}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Braket{\Psi_{f}|\Psi_{i}} & = & \int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi_{i}\left(x\in\Sigma_{i}\right),\phi_{f}\left(x\in\Sigma_{f}\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 &  & \times\Psi_{f}^{\star}\left[\phi_{f}\left(x\right)\right]\Braket{\phi_{f}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{f}|\phi_{i}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{i}}\Psi_{i}\left[\phi_{i}\left(x\right)\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the initial and final hypersurfaces are 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 respectively and by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 is later than 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 any future directed timelike curve passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 at proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 at a proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f}>\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 From this equation it is clear that the time evolution problem reduces
 to finding
