reference "eq:phi-eigenstate-transition-amplitude-pi"

\end_inset

 and deform the time contour in a slight negative imaginary direction, so
 that one eventually takes the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}\to-\infty\left(1-i\epsilon\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f}\to+\infty\left(1-i\epsilon\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The imaginary time component introduces a dissipative part to the time
 evolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\exp\left(-\epsilon t\hat{H}\right)$
\end_inset

 which damps all states except for the lowest energy, i.e.
 vacuum, state.
 So finally in the limit only the vacuum-to-vacuum matrix element survives
