\begin_layout Standard
This chapter has tried to motivate the investigation which forms the remainder
 of this thesis.
 This started with a general discussion of the gaps which exist between
 theory and experiment in situations involving strongly interacting particles
 and many particles out of equilibrium.
 Electroweak baryogenesis was then given as a concrete example and discussed
 in some detail, with an emphasis on those areas which have been hindered
 by an inability to compute.
 Then, laying the groundwork for the remainder of the thesis, basic quantum
 field theory was reviewed focusing on the functional integral formalism.
 It has been shown that a common formula for the generating functional can
 be used for scattering, thermal equilibrium and generic non-equilibrium
 problems by specifying a choice of time contour.
 The fundamental objects of field theory are the Green functions which can
 be straightforwardly connected to physical observables such as densities,
 currents and so forth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remainder of this thesis is structured as follows.
 Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap2"

\end_inset

 introduces the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-particle irreducible effective action (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA) techniques with an emphasis on their application to non-perturbative
 quantum field theory.
 This includes a review of the standard theory surrounding the methods and
 concludes with a novel investigation into the analytic properties of the
 solution of the 2PIEA in a toy model which can be compared to the exact
 solution and contrasted with other non-perturbative techniques.
 Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap3"

\end_inset

 begins the consideration of symmetries in the thesis by introducing the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O}\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 scalar field theory which forms the basis of the remainder of the work.
 The Ward identities for the theory (which encode the symmetries of the
 theory in effective action language) are derived and it is shown that the
 expected identities no longer hold for truncations of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA.
 This result is known in the literature but is derived here in a way which
 is, to the author's knowledge, new.
 The 2PIEA is then solved in the Hartree-Fock approximation demonstrating
 this result explicitly.
 A contrast is then drawn between these results and those of the external
 propagator method and large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 method.
 Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap4"

\end_inset

 introduces the symmetry improved 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA (SI-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA) as a means of overcoming the difficulty posed by violations of symmetries
 in truncated 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA.
 The novel work in this chapter is an extension of the symmetry improvement
 known in the literature from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O}\left(2\right),\mathrm{O}\left(4\right)\to\mathrm{O}\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 and from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\hbar^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 SI-2PIEA to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\hbar^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 SI-3PIEA.
 Additionally, several ambiguities in the original symmetry improvement
 procedure are identified and addressed.
 The renormalisation theory of these actions is discussed and solutions
 are presented in the Hartree-Fock approximation, as well as a few checks
 of the basic field theoretical consistency of the new actions.
 Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap5"

\end_inset

 introduces a novel technique called soft symmetry improvement (SSI) aimed
 at overcoming the difficulties of the SI-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA.
 The SSI-2PIEA is derived, renormalised and solved in the Hartree-Fock approxima
tion.
 It is shown that the method is sensitive to the way the infinite volume
 / low temperature limit is taken and there are three limiting cases: a
 trivial reduction to the unimproved 2PIEA, a reduction to the SI-2PIEA,
 and a novel limit which possess some unusual features which are discussed.
 Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap6"

\end_inset

 studies for the first time the non-equilibrium aspects of the SI-2PIEA
 by formulating the linear response theory for a system governed by the
 SI-2PIEA being driven away from equilibrium by a weak external perturbation.
 It is shown that the SI-2PIEA, and by a simple extension all SI-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA, are inconsistent with the linear response approximation.
 Finally, chapter 
